text.text: A Guide to Greenwich

After two days nosing about the home of time we can confirm there’s more to Greenwich than a pirate ship and a big hill. In fact, it may even be one of the most beautiful parts of the capital. It’s home to some of the best pubs for daytime drinking and great food backed by a plethora of overwhelmingly passionate restaurateurs– all of which are complimented by the postcode’s quaint country-side-within-the-city vibes.
Best for… getting crafty with your beer

tip.text: If creative brewing and phenomenal flavours are your vibe when it comes to booze, then you'll be impressed by The Greenwich Union. The astoundingly extensive list of craft beer on offer here is a spectacular nod to SE’s burgeoning brewing scene, and stocks over 200 bottles with 18 draft lines that the buzzing staff switch up on the regs.

tip.text: An inspirational hub of homemade goodness, where creative minds and delicate fingers collide. You'll always find horde of crafters knocking about selling top notch custom-made goodies here. Retro garms, street food, antiques, vintage knick knacks are also up for grabs. Plus it's set in a World Heritage site.

text.text: Sure, you'll find a lot of tourists as this spot but this is Greenwich, remember. The famous market is a thriving hub of homemade goodness, where creative minds and delicate fingers collide. You'll always find horde of crafters knocking about selling top notch custom-made goodies here. Retro garms, street food, antiques, vintage knick knacks are also up for grabs. Plus, it's set within a World Heritage site.
Best for... a cheap, BYOB eat

tip.text:
It may not look much from the outside, but on the inside... well... it still doesn't look like much. Zaibatsu is the ultimate sushi secret, where the £'s saved on an interior decorator have clearly been funnelled into the elaborate presentation of its Japanese fusion cuisine.

Zaibatsu seats around 20 people and serves some of the best (and cheapest) sushi we've tried south of the river. Go for… a bit of everything and share the love, people. If you’re feeling selfish, you can destroy a massive Katsu curry for around £6.

Better yet, it's BYOB with no corkage fee, woohoo. Cash only, and be sure to book ahead.

tip.text:
***Unpublished Feb 2019***

This sheepishly sexy little spot is all about getting back to basics. Cluttered chicly with furniture bought from local traders and a menu adorned with simple, elegantly sourced meats and cheese – Champagne + Fromage is a far cry from the yuppified haunt you may have heard about.

Everything on premises hails from small producers and all the fizz on offer is grower (not merchant) champagne.

text.text: This sheepishly sexy little spot is all about getting back to basics. Cluttered with furniture bought from local traders and a menu adorned with simple charcuteries and cheese – Champagne + Fromage is a far cry from the yuppified haunt you may have heard about. Everything on site hails from small producers and all the champagne on offer is from independent winemakers.
Best for… getting in the groove

tip.text:
If you manage to find Oliver’s (this gorgeously grubby jazz haven resides behind a heavily inconspicuous, tiny battered door) you’ll soon understand exactly why we’re gushing so much.

There’s only a single beer on tap backed up by a myriad of dusty bottles of wines and spirits at minuscule prices. You can expect it to be rammed with jazz lovers from across generations who have likely all booked ahead, as you should do. Now go do some groovin’ at this swinging jazz club.

text.text: If you manage to find Oliver’s, you’ll soon understand why we’re gushing. There’s only a single beer on tap, backed up by a myriad of dusty bottles of wine and spirits at minuscule prices. Shuffle down the flight of rickety stairs and you’ll find yourself crammed into an old basement adorned with snaps of jazz legends and good vibes.
Best for… more of that sushi

tip.text:
What would you expect from a Japanese-Danish collaboration? Minimalism, style and efficiency - and it wouldn’t be cheap. This slick and sexy sushi joint is just that, perfect for a fast and furious business lunch. Evenings are more ambient and relaxed, so grab one of the high tables and observe the bustle of the room from a vantage point.

Yes, the food is absolutely stunning but it will set you back a penny - the recommended sharing platter for newcomers, The Upgrade, is going for £65 between two - and ain’t exactly a tummy filler. Options include 14 set menus, combining both hot and cold dishes, as well as the à la carte option. Smash your piggy bank, treat yourself and go all out if you’re feeling brave.

text.text: Striving to constantly stay ahead of the curve, Sticks'n'Sushi packs affordable and delicious dishes. Plus, the fact that they buy radishes from the local primary school made our hearts melt a whole bunch. When glancing over the menu (that better resembles a piece of art than a list of grub) the kind staff also treated us to a few killer secrets – like their mackerel can’t be found anywhere else outside of Japan.
Best for… rolling like Charles Dickens

tip.text:
If it’s a "ye olde" pub your after, The Cutty Sark doesn’t mess around. This is what you called a Tavern. Yes, the food here bangs pretty hard, but we don’t want to waste too much time talking about that because this beautifully-preserved Georgian pub is like a time capsule from the 18th century and it’s not even very touristy. Score.

Test your wits at the Cutty Pub Quiz on Wednesdays at 8pm.

tip.text:
Pie and mash is a cultural cornerstone of our fine capital, so this particular outlet in the heart of peak-historical Greenwich makes for a perfect spot for a double serving of heritage - and a double serving of pie at that (you can double up for two quid). The original Goddards in Deptford opened in 1890 and this second brach in 1952 (that means it has been there as long as the Cutty Sark, which is pretty wild) and the decor feels like it probably hasn’t changed since.

The pies themselves are little discs of pastry that you crack open to find a steaming pocket of beef mince and a rich gravy, served with creamy mash and liquor (parsley sauce). You’re gonna wanna add some salt and vinegar, as is the way, and tuck straight in. Look out the window at the Old Royal Naval College and pretend you’re in the olden times, it’s fun.

text.text: Glorious 1920s-esque interior aside, there’s nothing more ‘London’ to real Londoners than a rich pie smothered with fluorescent green parsley liquor (not gravy, duh). One bite into the chunky crust, bold beef filling and lashings of creamy mash and you can see why. What’s more, these little slices of London are pretty darn cheap too.
Best for… banging views

tip.text:
After the short flight out to Greenwich, make for one of London's most prestigious bits of park real estate, a World Heritage Site where King Henry VIII once lumbered around chasing deer. The rolling green and leafy hills make it an ideal spot for those views - we'd suggest heading to One Tree Hill in particular for the widescreen panoramic. Stroll along the long avenues where 400-year-old Spanish chestnut trees give off some tasty edible nuts (we promise). Feel good.

Among the attractions here is the National Maritime Museum & Old Royal Naval College, as well as a sanctuary for deer, foxes, and birds. And, of course, the jewel in the crown: the Royal Observatory and Planetarium where it's possible to take a tour of... the UNIVERSE!

text.text: A mere scurry from London Bridge lies perhaps the city’s most gob-smacking green space, and where better to down a few tinnies on a sunny day. The lit views of the city are by far Greenwich Park’s biggest draw. But do be sure to pop by the flower garden and the pond, they're a total treat for the eyes.
Best for... escaping to the country for a little bit

tip.text: Sick to death of overcrowded wine bars and overpriced cocktail spots? Or just need some time away from the bleakness of London? Stroll over to The Hare & Billet, a true country pub hidden right beside the lovely Greenwich park, where the beer taps play host to independent brewers and the locals chat about family, football, politics and stuff. Expect classic pub grub, like the steak, the billet burger and the fish and chips, along with a few posher options, like the burrata with peas, broad beans, asparagus and olive tapenade - oolala.
